For this, we would need to use the formula for accounting break-even point. We can recall that at accounting break even, the company generates exactly zero profit. This can be solved using the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Q}&=\dfrac{\text{FC}+\text{D}}{\text{P}-\text{v}}
\end{aligned}$$

where

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{FC}&=\text{Fixed costs}\\
\text{D}&=\text{Depreciation}\\
\text{P}&=\text{Price per unit}\\
\text{v}&=\text{Variable price per unit}
\end{aligned}$$

Using this formula, we can manipulate it in order to solve for the other values.

For the first row, we can first plug in the known values:

$$\begin{aligned}
125,736&=\dfrac{\$820,000+\text{D}}{\$39-\$30}
\end{aligned}$$

As we can see, we are looking for the depreciation. Combine the terms that can be combined:

$$\begin{aligned}
125,736&=\dfrac{\$820,000+\text{D}}{\$9}
\end{aligned}$$

For the second row, plug in the known values first:

$$\begin{aligned}
165,000&=\dfrac{\$2,320,000+\$975,000}{\text{P}-\$27}
\end{aligned}$$

For the third row, plug in the known values first:

$$\begin{aligned}
21,430&=\dfrac{\$237,000-\$128,700}{\$92-\text{v}}
\end{aligned}$$
